[{"id":"VR598927","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">Read each question carefully. Show all your work for each part of the question. The parts within the question may not have equal weight.</p><br/><div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Two figures are shown. Each figure shows a solid uniform disk supported by a vertical stand in two stages labeled Figure 1 and Figure 2. In each figure, an axle at the top of the stand passes through the center of the disk. The radius of the disk is labeled R. A string passes over the top of each disk. In Figure 1, the disk is at rest and the point P is indicated on the edge of the disk, directly above the center of the disk. The right side of the string has nothing attached to it. The left side of the string is attached to the top end of an unstretched spring that is vertically oriented. The bottom end of the spring is attached to the ground. In Figure 2, the disk is being pulled to the right at an angle of theta from the vertical, such that point P is now above and to the right of the center of the disk. The right side of the string is now attached to a block. The left side of the string is attached to the top end of the spring, which is now stretched. The bottom end of the spring is attached to the ground.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR598927.g24.svg\"/></div>\n<p class=\"passage_para\">A solid uniform disk is supported by a vertical stand. The disk is able to rotate with negligible friction about an axle that passes through the center of the disk. The mass and radius of the disk are given by <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"M sub d\"><math alttext=\"M sub d\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>M</mi><mtext>d</mtext></msub></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R\"><math alttext=\"R\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>R</mi></math></span></span>, respectively. The rotational inertia of the disk is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I sub d equals, one half M sub d, end sub, times R squared\"><math alttext=\"I sub d equals, one half M sub d, end sub, times R squared\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mtext>d</mtext></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msub><mi>M</mi><mtext>d</mtext></msub><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></span></span>. A string of negligible mass is draped over the disk and attached to the top of the disk at point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>P</mtext></math></span></span>. One end of the string is connected to an unstretched ideal spring of spring constant <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"k\"><math alttext=\"k\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>k</mi></math></span></span>, which is fixed to the ground as shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span>.</p>\n<p class=\"passage_para\">A block of mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"m sub B\"><math alttext=\"m sub B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>m</mi><mtext>B</mtext></msub></math></span></span> is then attached to the string on the right side of the disk. The block is slowly lowered until the spring-disk-block system reaches equilibrium, as shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>. In this equilibrium position, the disk has rotated clockwise through a small angle <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta\"><math alttext=\"theta\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>θ</mi></math></span></span>.</p>\n<p class=\"passage_para\">Give all algebraic answers in terms of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"M sub d\"><math alttext=\"M sub d\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>M</mi><mtext>d</mtext></msub></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R\"><math alttext=\"R\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>R</mi></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"k\"><math alttext=\"k\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>k</mi></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta\"><math alttext=\"theta\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>θ</mi></math></span></span>, and physical constants, as appropriate.</p>\n</div></div></div></div><div class=\"item_part part_id:A part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"A\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(a) Derive an expression for the mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"m sub B\"><math alttext=\"m sub B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>m</mi><mtext>B</mtext></msub></math></span></span> of the block.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR598927_rubric"},{"id":"VR598927","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:B part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"B\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(b) At time <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t equals 0\"><math alttext=\"t equals 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></span></span>, the string on the right side of the disk is cut and the block falls to the ground. On the circle below, which represents the disk, draw and label the forces (not components) that act on the disk immediately after the string is cut and the block is falling to the ground. Each force should be represented by an arrow that starts on and is directed away from the point of application.</p><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a circle, which represents the disk from Figures 1 and 2. A dot is drawn at the center. A dashed line slants upward and to the right through the circle and intersects the dot at the center.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR598927.g25.svg\"/></div></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR598927_rubric"},{"id":"VR598927","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:C part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"C\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(c) Derive an expression for the angular acceleration <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"alpha\"><math alttext=\"alpha\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>α</mi></math></span></span> of the disk immediately after the string is cut.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR598927_rubric"},{"id":"VR598927","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:D part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"D\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(d) At <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t equals t sub 1\"><math alttext=\"t equals t sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>, the disk has rotated and point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>P</mtext></math></span></span> is again directly above the axle. Sketch a graph of the magnitude of the angular velocity <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"omega\"><math alttext=\"omega\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>ω</mi></math></span></span> of the disk as a function of time <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t\"><math alttext=\"t\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>t</mi></math></span></span> from <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t equals 0\"><math alttext=\"t equals 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></span></span> to <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t equals t sub 1\"><math alttext=\"t equals t sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>.</p><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows the first quadrant of a coordinate plane. The horizontal axis is labeled t, and the vertical axis is labeled omega. The value t sub 1 is indicated about two thirds of the way along the horizontal axis. A dashed vertical line extends upward through the plane from the value t sub 1.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR598927.g26.svg\"/></div></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR598927_rubric"},{"id":"VR598927","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:E part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"E\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Figure 3 shows the same setup of the disk as in Figure 2; however, the stand is positioned such that the axle does not pass through the center of the disk, but instead passes through a point directly to the left of the center.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR598927.g27.svg\"/></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(e) The disk is adjusted on the support so that the axle does <span class=\"formatted_text text_decoration:underline\">not</span> pass through the center of mass (cm) of the disk. The block is again hung on the right side of the disk and the spring-disk-block system comes to equilibrium, as shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span>. The axle does not exert a torque on the disk. For each force on the disk, indicate whether the magnitude of the torque about the axle caused by that force increases, decreases, or stays the same relative to part (b).</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR598927_rubric"}]